    excerpt: 'Atari Breakout is the classic arcade game that started it all.',
    content: `<p>Atari Breakout is the classic arcade game that started it all. You control a paddle at the bottom of the screen and bounce a ball upward to destroy rows of coloured blocks. Miss the ball and you lose a life. Clear all the blocks and you move on to the next round. It&#8217;s simple, addictive, and just as fun now as it was back in 1976.</p>

<p>The original game was designed by Steve Wozniak, the co-founder of Apple, along with Nolan Bushnell and Steve Bristow. It was inspired by Atari Pong and became one of the most influential arcade games ever made. The Coolmath Games version stays true to that classic feel while adding a few extra modes to keep things interesting.</p>

<p>What makes Atari Breakout so satisfying is how easy it is to pick up but how tricky it gets the longer you play. The ball speeds up as you progress, and timing your paddle movements becomes more important. One wrong move and the ball slips past you. It&#8217;s the kind of game where you always want one more try.</p>

<p>The game rewards patience and precision over speed. Rushing usually ends badly. Learning how the ball bounces off different parts of your paddle helps you aim for specific blocks, especially when you&#8217;re trying to clear the last few stubborn ones at the end of a round.</p>

<h2 class="wp-block-heading"><strong>How To Play Atari Breakout</strong></h2>

<p>Playing Atari Breakout is straightforward. Use your mouse, arrow keys, or A and D keys to move the paddle left and right. Press space or click to launch the ball. From there, just keep bouncing it back up to break the blocks.</p>

<p>The Coolmath Games version includes four different modes. Standard mode is the classic experience with one ball and one paddle. Double mode gives you two balls to juggle at once, which gets chaotic fast. Cavity mode starts with one ball but has extra balls trapped inside the blocks that you can free. Progressive mode has the wall of blocks slowly moving downward, adding pressure to clear them quickly.</p>

<p>Where the ball hits your paddle affects where it goes next. Hit it with the edge and it flies off at a sharp angle. Hit it dead centre and it goes straight up with less speed. Learning to control this is key to aiming for specific blocks, especially when trying to break through one side and get the ball behind the wall for maximum damage.</p>

<p>Each completed round earns you 468 points. A solid goal for beginners is to clear five rounds, which adds up to 2,340 points. The further you go, the faster things get, so stay focused and don&#8217;t panic.</p>
<div class='code-block code-block-1' style='margin: 8px auto; text-align: center; display: block; clear: both;'>

</div>
<!-- CONTENT END 1 -->`,
